            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How the Canada payroll calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This Canada payroll calculator estimates CPP/QPP, EI, and income
                tax based on your province or territory, pay frequency, and
                income. It is designed to be fast and transparent, so you can
                see how each deduction affects your net pay.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Gross pay per period</h3>
              <p>
                The first step is to determine gross pay for the pay period:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hourly</strong>:
                  <code>gross = hourly rate × hours per period</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Salary</strong>:
                  <code>gross = salary per period</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bonus / commission</strong>:
                  <code>gross = bonus amount</code> (treated as a one-time
                  payment)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Annual gross pay is then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >annual gross = gross per period × pay periods per year</code
                >
              </div>

              <h3>2. CPP / QPP contributions</h3>
              <p>
                For most employees outside Quebec, the calculator uses Canada
                Pension Plan (CPP) rules. For Quebec, it uses Quebec Pension
                Plan (QPP) rates and maximums. Contributions are based on
                <em>pensionable earnings</em> between the basic exemption and
                the annual maximum.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>CPP/QPP pensionable earnings</strong> (annual) ≈</p>
                <code
                  >max(0, min(annual gross, yearly maximum) − basic
                  exemption)</code
                >
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>CPP/QPP contribution</strong> (annual) ≈
                </p>
                <code>pensionable earnings × contribution rate</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator also lets you enter
                <strong>YTD pensionable earnings</strong> so that CPP/QPP stops
                once the annual maximum contribution is reached.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Employment Insurance (EI)</h3>
              <p>
                EI premiums are calculated on <em>insurable earnings</em> up to
                the annual maximum insurable earnings. The tool applies the
                current EI rate and caps contributions at the yearly maximum,
                adjusted for any YTD income you enter.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >EI annual = min(annual gross, EI maximum insurable earnings)
                  × EI rate</code
                >
              </div>

              <h3>4. Federal and provincial income tax</h3>
              <p>
                Income tax is estimated using simplified progressive tax
                brackets for the selected year and province/territory. The
                calculator:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Computes <strong>taxable income</strong> as annual gross minus
                  CPP/QPP and EI.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Applies <strong>federal brackets</strong> to get gross federal
                  tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Applies <strong>provincial/territorial brackets</strong> to
                  get gross provincial tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts basic personal amounts and any additional
                  non-refundable credits you enter.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>Conceptually:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >federal tax = (tax on taxable income using federal brackets)
                  − (federal credits × 15%)</code
                ><br />
                <code
                  >provincial tax = (tax on taxable income using provincial
                  brackets) − (provincial credits × lowest provincial
                  rate)</code
                >
              </div>
              <p>
                The result is divided by the number of pay periods to estimate
                tax per paycheque. For Quebec, the calculator uses
                Quebec-specific tax rates in a simplified way.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Net pay</h3>
              <p>Net pay per period is simply:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >net pay = gross pay − CPP/QPP − EI − federal tax −
                  provincial/territorial tax</code
                >
              </div>

              <h2>Limitations and compliance notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This is an <strong>educational estimator</strong>, not a
                  replacement for CRA’s Payroll Deductions Online Calculator.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Some items are <strong>not</strong> handled: union dues, group
                  benefits, RRSP contributions, taxable benefits, WCB, QPIP, and
                  other province-specific programs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Quebec payroll is more complex; always verify with Revenu
                  Québec and CRA tools.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Employers remain responsible for correct source deductions and
                  remittances.
                </li>
              </ul>

